member.returns:
            The subsets of the list. For example, if the input array is { 1, 2, 3 }, the output
            should be as follows:


{ 1 }

{ 2 }

{ 3 }

{ 1, 2 }

{ 1, 3 }

{ 2, 3 }

{ 1, 2, 3 }

            7 cases (without null set) in total.

member.remarks:
A closed enumeration type is a type that only holds the value in the enumeration declaration field (i.e. the curly bracket). For example, the code
[Closed] public enum Gender { Boy; Girl; }
Which means the type Gender is a closed enumeration type, you can't use arithmetic operators to get the fields that don't appear in the declaration { Boy; Girl; }. In other words, you can only use those fields as the references, instead of any calculations.

member.summary:
Append the text into the tail of the  object if
the text is not , and then add a terminator at the tail;
otherwise, do nothing.

member.example:
You can use this struct like this:

var sb = new ValueStringBuilder(stackalloc char[100]);

// Appending operations...
sb.Append("Hello");
sb.Append(',');
sb.Append("World");
sb.Append('!');

Console.WriteLine(sb.ToString()); // Dispose method will be called here.

remarks.para:
You can also use the constructor:  like:

var sb = new ValueStringBuilder(10);

The code is nearly equivalent to

var sb = new ValueStringBuilder(stackalloc char[10]);

but uses shared array pool (i.e. the property )
to create the buffer rather than using .

The dispose method will be called during this method executed. Therefore, in C# 8, even if we can use the syntax
using var sb = new ValueStringBuilder(stackalloc char[10]);
we won't use the keyword before object creation expression.
